#include<stdio.h>

int main()
{
    int a[10], n, i, j, temp, flag;

    printf("Enter number of elements: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    printf("Enter elements:\n");

    for(i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        scanf("%d", &a[i]);
    }

    // Bubble Sort
    for(i = 0; i < n - 1; i++)
    {
        flag = 0;

        for(j = 0; j < n - 1 - i; j++)
        {
            if(a[j] > a[j + 1])
            {
                temp = a[j];
                a[j] = a[j + 1];
                a[j + 1] = temp;

                flag = 1;
            }
        }

        if(flag == 0)
        {
            break;
        }
    }

    printf("Sorted elements:\n");

    for(i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        printf("%d ", a[i]);
    }

    return 0;
}


/*
Bubble Sort in C

This program sorts elements in ascending order using the Bubble Sort technique.

Algorithm Idea

Bubble Sort repeatedly compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are in the wrong order.

Compare two nearby elements

Swap if left element is greater

Largest element moves to the end after each pass

Repeat until array becomes sorted


Time Complexity

Best Case: O(n) → already sorted (flag helps)

Average Case: O(n²)

Worst Case: O(n²)


Key Variables

temp → used for swapping

flag → checks whether swapping happened

flag == 0 → array already sorted, stop early


Advantages

Simple and beginner friendly

Easy to implement

Good for small datasets


Disadvantages

Slow for large data

More comparisons and swaps


Applications

Educational purposes

Small data sorting

When simplicity is more important than efficiency


Example

Input:

5
5 1 4 2 3

Output:

1 2 3 4 5

Logic Flow

Compare → Swap → Largest element bubbles to end → Repeat

Memory Trick

“Large elements bubble up to the end like air bubbles in water.”*/